Characterizes a bolted connection between two bodies.
Use bolt connectors to mathematically represent threaded fasteners that hold together an assembly. Avoid spending time and effort to produce, mesh, and solve solid models of fastener parts.

Specify the subtype as a nut or threaded hole bolt type of connection. You can include an optional washer at either end. Enter the size, preload and material of the bolt to ensure accurate representation of the connection.
The amount of elements required to accurately capture threads and the modeling time to align bolt threads to hole threads can all be avoided by using Bolt Connectors.
Head and nut locations can only be applied to circular edges. Select a cylindrical surface to indicate thread location.
Rigidly connect a vertex on a body to faces, edges or vertices on another body
There are two subtypes of rigid body connectors, this should be specified first. The second selection will be a vertex. The third selection can include one or more faces, edges, or vertices:

Rigid body: The first vertex selected is the Anchor Point, which is the independent vertex. The motion of the entities in the second set is dependent on the motion of the Anchor Point. The dependent entities move exactly as the independent vertex moves.

Interpolation: The first vertex you select is a Reference Point. The items in the second selection are independent entities to average. In this case, the Reference Point is the dependent entity (its motion is controlled by the motion of the independent entities). The weighted average of the displacement of the independent entitites is applied to the reference point.
Vertices must be specified on a 3D object. Creating a small cone or block can be useful to further reduce the complexity of your model.
Note: You can connect an Anchor Point or Reference point on a body to a set of faces, edges, or vertices on the same body (for example to represent a brace or strut that reinforces the body.
Provides an elastic connection between two vertices.
A spring can connect two vertices on the same part or two different parts.
The amount of elements required to accurately capture the long thin helical geometry of a spring can be avoided by using a Spring Connector.
Select the two vertices that would be the spring endpoints then add the performance criteria of the spring.
Prevent displacement of one or more entities.
By default, a Fixed constraint prevents movement in all directions. Use the Axis buttons to allow movement in specified directions.
Prevent displacement normal to the selected face or faces.
Use Frictionless Constraints to allow movement in the plane of the assigned constraint, but not away from or into it.
An example is an object on a track. The object can move along the track, but cannot separate from the track.
Prevent displacement of one or more cylindrical surfaces.
Use Pinned Constraints to prevent radial, axial, and/or tangential displacement of cylindrical surfaces.
Radial pin constraints prevent the surface from colliding with or separating from the pin.
Axial pin constraints prevent the surface from moving along the length of the pin.
Tangential pin constraints prevent rotation about the circumference of the pin.
